## Abstract

This paper does not attempt to explain quantum mechanics through any single theory, but rather adopts a meta-descriptive framework to observe and express its structural character.

This framework does not belong to quantum mechanics itself, but is used to describe the structural relationships between different quantum interpretations.

The meta-descriptive perspective adopted in this paper is consistent with the author’s Trust Framework and Meta-System Theory, but this paper does not depend on their complete development. Rather, as an independent text, it presents the structural relationships of quantum interpretation systems.

This paper proposes that quantum physics is not an incomplete system struggling to reach classical reality, but rather the complete and perfect instantiation of the Possibility stage within the universal Meta-System. Different quantum interpretations are not competing theories but different signal-dependent responses to the same structural problem: how does a system maintain its possibility space while enabling transition to actuality under conditions of measurement uncertainty?

By examining the structural relationship between superposition, measurement, collapse, and continuation, this paper demonstrates how the four irreducible dimensions of any complete system (釋構度行: Interpretation-Structure-Regime-Operation) are fully instantiated in quantum physics. Each of the five major quantum interpretations (Copenhagen, Many-Worlds, Pilot-Wave, Objective Collapse, Relational) represents a different prioritization of signal interpretation, yet all remain structurally unified within the sequence:

Superposition → Measurement Signal → Expectation Formation → Trust Collapse → State Manifestation → Continuation

This framework provides a structured perspective for understanding quantum mechanics not as incomplete, but as the complete realization of how Possibility must operate in any system seeking continuation.

